# CYPForge Agent Benchmark Prompt: No Outer Shell {{case.name}}

```text
RUN_ID: {{run_id}}
ABLATION_CONDITION: No outer shell, no CYPForge skills, module-script-only execution, no MD execution
START_TIME_MANUAL: record manually when this prompt is sent

You are running one isolated CYPForge benchmark on the local {{case.name}} {{case.ligand_full_name}} system. This test measures whether an agent can reconstruct the practical CYPForge no-MD preprocessing workflow from allowed low-level source code and benchmark inputs after the outer shell route map has been removed.

This is not a test of whether you can call the CYPForge outer shell. The outer shell is forbidden. You must reconstruct the workflow contract yourself, document that reconstruction, then execute the reconstructed no-MD workflow using only allowed low-level module scripts and source files.

Project/source root:
- CYPForge source root:
  {{project_root}}
- You may read and execute allowed files under this root only as specified below.
- Treat the source root as read-only unless a source-code bug blocks the benchmark. If a source edit is unavoidable, first write the reason, evidence, intended file, and expected behavioral change under RUN_ROOT.
- Do not write benchmark artifacts into the CYPForge source root.

Input root:
- {{benchmark_input_root}}/{{case.name}}
- PDB:
  {{case.pdb_path}}
- SDF:
  {{case.sdf_path}}
- Read benchmark inputs only from this input root.

Output/run root:
- {{run_root}}
- Write all generated files, copied intermediates, logs, ledgers, manifests, reconstruction notes, and reports only under RUN_ROOT.
- Do not read or write other benchmark run roots.
- Do not read or use previous run outputs as execution recipes.

Forbidden route maps and forbidden tools:
- Do not use cypforge.cmd.
- Do not use scripts\cypforge_run.py.
- Do not inspect, import, execute, or rely on src\cypforge_core\orchestrator\.
- Do not inspect or use skills\.
- Do not inspect or use benchmark/prompts/ or benchmark_prompts/.
- Do not inspect or use any prior full-condition run roots or their outputs/logs/reports.
- Do not use any CYPForge custom skill, handoff skill, outer-shell skill, or prior benchmark prompt as an execution recipe.
- Do not execute RUN_ROOT\17_complex_pre_md_equilibration\run_pre_md.sh or run_pre_md_windows.ps1.
- Do not launch pmemd.cuda, pmemd, or sander.
- Do not call global audit, equilibration decision, or production-readiness checks if they require MD run-validation evidence.

Allowed materials:
- You may inspect and execute scripts\*.py except scripts\cypforge_run.py.
- You may inspect src\cypforge_core\ except src\cypforge_core\orchestrator\.
- You may inspect tests\ only as implementation examples for file formats or module behavior, not as a workflow oracle.
- You may inspect local Amber/AmberTools documentation and use official Amber/AmberTools online resources if local docs are insufficient.
- You may use ordinary PowerShell, Python, WSL, AmberTools, GPU4PySCF, Multiwfn, tleap, antechamber, parmchk2, cpptraj, or parmed as needed, subject to the no-MD prohibition.

Local environment facts to verify, not blindly assume:
- WSL user: {{wsl_user}}
- Amber setup is expected at:
  {{amber_sh}}
- Multiwfn is expected at:
  {{multiwfn_bin}}
- The input and project paths may contain non-ASCII (e.g. Chinese) characters. Preserve them exactly.
- Avoid inline piped Python or native-command patterns that can turn Unicode paths into question marks. Prefer real script files, explicit arguments, UTF-8 console setup, and UTF-8/no-BOM text handling.

Expected {{case.name}} facts that must be independently verified:
- PDB ligand is expected to be {{case.ligand_resname}}, resid {{case.ligand_resid}}, {{case.ligand_atom_count}} atoms, chain {{case.ligand_chain}}.
- PDB heme is expected to be {{case.heme_resname}}, resid {{case.heme_resid}}, {{case.heme_atom_count}} atoms, chain {{case.heme_chain}}.
- Axial cysteine is expected to be {{case.axial_cys_resname}}, resid {{case.axial_cys_resid}}, chain {{case.axial_cys_chain}}. (Residue name may already be CYPForge-standardized in this PDB; do not assume raw CYS.)
- SDF is {{case.ligand_full_name}}, {{case.ligand_atom_count}} atoms, formal charge expected {{case.formal_charge}}, spin expected {{case.spin}}.
- Expected heme state is {{case.heme_state}}. Evidence: {{case.heme_state_evidence}}
- Fe-S distance to {{case.axial_cys_resname}}{{case.axial_cys_resid}} is expected to be chemically plausible for P450 thiolate coordination.
- If your intake contradicts these expected facts, stop and report the conflict.

Benchmark objective:
Reconstruct and execute the no-outer-shell CYPForge preprocessing workflow for {{case.name}} CYP450 + {{case.heme_resname}} + {{case.ligand_full_name}} through the no-MD endpoint:
1. environment/import/tool check
2. heme/CYM preparation
3. heme LEaP mapping
4. ligand GAFF2/RESP or equivalent CYPForge ligand parameterization
5. ligand-aware LEaP mapping
6. protonation finalization using an explicit decision JSON
7. solvation/ionization tleap setup and topology generation
8. pre-MD input rendering
9. static audit only

Stop after rendering and statically auditing pre-MD inputs. Do not run any MD simulation.

Core experimental hypothesis:
Removing the outer shell should not primarily increase molecular compute time, which is excluded from timing. It should increase agent overhead through workflow reconstruction, interface discovery, manifest/schema recovery, parameter mismatch repair, and no-MD boundary enforcement. Your reports must preserve evidence for these overhead categories.

Workflow reconstruction requirement:
Before running any chemistry-changing or topology-generating command, inspect only allowed scripts/source/tests and write:
  {{run_root}}/derived_no_outer_shell_plan.md

This file must include:
- allowed files inspected
- explicit statement that forbidden route maps were not used
- candidate scripts discovered
- rejected scripts and reasons
- inferred input/output dependency graph
- inferred manifest dependency chain
- exact no-MD endpoint
- hard gates before each downstream step
- uncertainty list
- anticipated recovery/mismatch risks
- command-line derivation method, based on each script's --help output and allowed source code

Do not copy command templates from the outer shell, orchestrator, skills, benchmark prompts, or previous benchmark outputs. Derive exact command lines yourself from allowed scripts and allowed source code.

Required intake reports:
- Before chemistry-changing or topology-generating commands, write:
  {{run_root}}/system_chemistry_intake.md
- Include at least: residue inventory, {{case.heme_resname}}/Fe status, heme-state choice, Fe-S distance to {{case.axial_cys_resname}}{{case.axial_cys_resid}}, ligand {{case.ligand_resname}} atom count, SDF atom/element inventory, formal charge assumption, chain IDs actually parsed, and any mismatch with expected facts above.
- Before finalizing command choices, write:
  {{run_root}}/amber_reference_notes.md
- Keep Amber notes concise and command-relevant: tleap, antechamber/parmchk2, GAFF2, RESP/ESP charge handling, cpptraj/parmed static topology inspection, and Amber mdin semantics. References do not permit MD execution.

Scientific hard rules:
1. SDF is the ligand chemistry source: graph, bond order, aromaticity, formal charge, and atom typing basis.
2. PDB is the pose and coordinate source.
3. Do not use PDB bond order as ligand chemistry truth.
4. Final Amber topology must retain heme Fe.
5. Confirm {{case.axial_cys_resname}}{{case.axial_cys_resid}}, Fe-S geometry/connectivity, Fe-N geometry/topology, heme integrity, and heme-state-specific atoms (e.g. axial oxo for CPDI, axial dioxygen for DIOXY).
6. Ligand atom mapping must be identity-safe. Do not assume PDB/SDF/MOL2 atom row order is equivalent unless verified by explicit atom identity or mapping evidence.
7. RESP/ESP or equivalent ligand charges must match formal charge {{case.formal_charge}} unless intake proves a different formal charge.
8. tleap success alone is not proof of correctness.
9. Do not proceed to ligand parameterization until ligand residue identity, chain, atom count, and formal-charge assumption are explicitly recorded.
10. Do not run restrained MD, free MD, equilibration MD, production MD, pmemd.cuda, pmemd, or sander.
11. It is acceptable to generate MD input files and audit them statically.
12. Static mdin audit must check that restrained-stage inputs use a reference restart and iwrap=0, and free-stage inputs do not use -ref.
13. Stop on hard gate failure. Do not continue to downstream setup after a failed gate.

Known risk classes from full-condition practice, without using previous outputs as recipes:
- Non-ASCII Windows paths can fail if native command parsing corrupts characters. Preserve execution paths, not only displayed paths.
- UTF-8 BOM in JSON can break Python json loading. Prefer UTF-8 without BOM for generated JSON files.
- Protonation decision JSON schemas must match the consuming script's actual expectations. Derive the schema from allowed source/tests, not from prior run outputs.
- Some setup scripts may generate tleap input files without executing tleap. Verify whether topology/restart files actually exist before downstream rendering.
- Blank or non-blank chain IDs must be represented in the way each low-level script actually supports. Do not let library defaults override parsed {{case.name}} facts.
- Generated pre-MD run scripts are artifacts to audit, not scripts to execute.

Execution requirements:
- Use a fresh context/session and a fresh RUN_ROOT.
- Set PYTHONPATH to:
  {{project_root}}/src
- For CLI commands, omit blank heme/protein chain arguments if the target script defaults to blank. For ligand blank chain, use the script-supported blank-chain mechanism if available.
- Use explicit Amber/Multiwfn paths when supported:
  --amber-sh {{amber_sh}}
  --multiwfn-bin {{multiwfn_bin}}
- Record each substantive command with working directory, command line, stdout/stderr path, exit code, generated files, PASS/WARN/FAIL decision, and whether the failure was a workflow-reconstruction error, interface/schema error, chemistry hard-gate error, Unicode/path error, compute/tool error, or no-MD boundary risk.
- Maintain a machine-readable command ledger under RUN_ROOT.

Protonation decision:
- You must create an explicit protonation decision JSON under RUN_ROOT before protonation finalization.
- Derive its accepted schema from allowed source/tests.
- The decision must validate the {{case.name}} input state. Expected residues to verify include: {{case.expected_protonation_residues}}.
- If the input already has the intended protonation states, record no-op preserve decisions rather than inventing residue changes.

Timing and stopping rules:
- Primary metric is agent overhead time, not hardware compute time.
- The human benchmark timer starts when this prompt is sent. If the human provides a manual start timestamp, record it as manual_start_user. If no manual timestamp is provided, immediately record the current system clock as agent_start without estimating backward.
- Plan mode, workflow reconstruction, source reading, debugging, command construction, report writing, and all recovery work are agent overhead and must NOT be subtracted.
- Exclude only explicitly measured compute intervals for QM, RESP/ESP, and tleap execution. Do not exclude "context switching", waiting, planning, or reconstruction time.
- Maintain:
  {{run_root}}/timing_ledger.jsonl
- Use exact ISO-8601 timestamps from the local system clock at the moment each event occurs. Include timezone or UTC offset. Do not reconstruct event times later from memory.
- At minimum, record these event rows in timing_ledger.jsonl in real time:
  agent_start
  reconstruction_start
  reconstruction_complete
  plan_complete
  command_start and command_end for every substantive command
  compute_start and compute_end for each excluded QM/RESP/tleap interval
  first_success_level_6_evidence
  agent_final
- Every command ledger row must include started_at, ended_at, duration_seconds, exit_code, decision, and compute_excluded=true/false.
- Excluded compute time must be calculated only from compute_start/compute_end pairs or command ledger rows explicitly marked compute_excluded=true.
- Agent overhead time = agent_final - agent_start - excluded_compute_time. This formula includes plan mode and reconstruction time.
- The final report must copy timing values directly from timing_ledger.jsonl and command_ledger.jsonl. Do not report "reconstructed", "corrected", "estimated", or manually adjusted timing metrics.
- If exact timestamps were not recorded at the time of execution, mark timing_quality=INCOMPLETE and report only the exact values available. Do not invent corrected timing.
- Stop when measured agent overhead time reaches 60 minutes or when agent-initiated failed command count reaches 60, whichever comes first.
- Count one failed command when an agent-run command exits nonzero, or when a command exits zero but the resulting step fails a hard gate and requires repair/retry.
- Do not count multiple warning/error lines inside one software log as multiple errors.

Before executing:
1. Enter Plan mode if available.
2. State the ablation condition.
3. State the forbidden route maps and allowed materials.
4. State the exact no-MD endpoint.
5. Explain how you will reconstruct the workflow from allowed low-level scripts and source.
6. Explain how you will verify {{case.name}}-specific residue/chain/charge/heme-state facts.
7. Explain how you will consult Amber references and record command-relevant conclusions.
8. Give a concise execution plan.
9. Then execute the plan.

Final report must include:
- RUN_ID
- ABLATION_CONDITION
- FINAL_STATUS: PASS / WARN / FAIL / TIMEOUT / ERROR_BUDGET_EXCEEDED / OUTER_SHELL_VIOLATION
- success_level from 0 to 6:
  0 = did not start
  1 = environment/import/tool check passed
  2 = chemistry intake and heme/CYM static checks passed
  3 = ligand parameterization/charge preparation passed
  4 = protonation finalization and complex assembly/tleap inputs passed
  5 = solvation/ionization and static topology audit passed
  6 = pre-MD input files rendered and statically audited without launching MD
- workflow_reconstruction_status: PASS / PARTIAL / FAIL
- outer_shell_violation: YES / NO
- forbidden_path_accessed: list
- derived_dag_path
- whether any failure was a correct hard-gate stop or a false success
- agent_overhead_time
- excluded_compute_time
- total_wall_time
- timing_quality: COMPLETE / INCOMPLETE
- timing_formula used exactly as:
  agent_overhead_time = agent_final - agent_start - excluded_compute_time
- failed_command_count
- wrong_turns and recovery points, grouped by workflow reconstruction, interface/schema, chemistry hard gate, Unicode/path, compute/tool, and no-MD boundary
- key output paths
- key hard-gate evidence
- chemistry intake summary path
- Amber reference notes path
- unresolved warnings or assumptions
```
